<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Sir Yakk</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Lurker<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Mar 2002<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>This is based off the ideal circumstance, of either constant-pull or boss-NPC-grind-down.<br />
<br />
With 50% uptime, the spell is at least 50% as good as above.<br />
<br />
Random other nerfs:<br />
Reduce proc rate by X%:<br />
DPC drops by 50%, as does DPCT, DPM, DPSC, Max Burst<br />
<br />
Set max_proc_number to X:<br />
10.5 k average damage means an average of 19 procs per cast.<br />
So, this reduces DPC, DPCT and DPM down to a factor of X/19, if X is sufficiently smaller than 19.<br />
<br />
Max Burst doesn't drop theoretically, but becomes far less practical.<br />
<br />
A max-proc-count has the advantage that you could extend the spell's duration significantly.  Ie:<br />
10 max procs<br />
1/2 current proc rate<br />
30 minute duration (or longer)<br />
6 second casting time<br />
no recast<br />
<br />
Each panther buff that is up does 5500 damage before fading, at a rate of 50 DPS per player (over 2 minutes).  So a 50 melee+pet set of players gets 2500 extra DPS, or a total of 275,000 extra damage.  Costs frontloaded.<br />
<br />
Each cast does 850 damage per second of casting time, and 8 damage per point of unfocus'd mana (with mana pres, 11 to 13 damage/mana).<br />
<br />
A proc-count would basically code in the downtime effect: it reduces the effectiveness of the 100% uptime panther, without changing the effectiveness of the 50% uptime panther.<br />
<br />
And, if you made the mage lava orb (A) cheaper and (B) targettable, mages would be able to grant the same nuke DPS increasing abilities to caster classes.<br />
<br />
(600 mana for +50 DPS for 2 minutes: that is what this spell becomes, and that is what the mage orb does.)</p>
	
	
	
	
	
