<br />
If that is correct so far (I'm counting on people to provide better wizard numbers), that would make the two essentially equal, for max theoretical burst dps.  (I'm sure there is error built in at the moment; the difference of 9 dps is inconsequential within that margin of error.)<br />
<br />
Now, these situations are not normal.  We don't set up raids in order to maximize wizards dps; we don't set up raids in order to maximize shaman dps.  These are only calculations of what <i>might</i> be possible, if we were to stack the deck in order to maximize the dps of one character.<br />
<br />
I'll offer three preliminary conclusions.<br />
<br />
First, even though these are theoretical numbers rather than numbers you would get in ordinary practice, people at SOE will consider that a shaman should not in theory be able to match a wizard's max burst dps.<br />
<br />
Second, the wizard's theoretical burst dps comes from the wizard chain nuking the target boss mob.  The shaman's theoretical burst dps comes from chain buffing 18 other characters, who then actually cause the damage.  The wizard's dps is direct; the shaman's is cooperative.  That means that a straight comparison might not be appropriate:  it is comparing apples to oranges.<br />
<br />
Third, some sort of decision needs to be made as to what level of cooperative dps is the maximum that we think a shaman should be able to provide.  If a shaman can buff 18 people to provide an additional 1000 dps, is that all right?  800? 600?  What level of cooperative dps is acceptable to be accomplished with shaman buffs?<br />
<br />
(As an aside.  If you have 30 active melee characters on a raid -- warrior monk rogue paladin shadowknight ranger berserker beastlord beastpet magepet necropet -- who provide an average of 150 dps while fighting <i>unhasted</i>:  then one enchanter casting one (!!) mgb 70% haste provides 3150 cooperative dps for the next hour.  Assuming that that's zero while we are moving or standing around, and that during trash pulls we are sloppy, but during a three minute boss fight we are all pretty attentive:  we will claim 75% efficiency during the three minute boss fight.  The enchanter's cooperative dps during that fight -- off of a buff cast 40 minutes ago -- is 2362 dps.  More than the wizard's and the shaman's theoretical max combined.  And that's a real number that would show up in any raid, not a theoretical one calculated off of trying to figure out what's the max possible.)</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>You are messing up the math.  Ancient: Core Fire, is  <br />
<br />
Ancient Core Fire 	Detail | History | Raw Data<br />
 <br />
Slot 	Description<br />
1: 	Decrease Hitpoints by 4070<br />
 <br />
Mana: 	850 	Skill: 	Evocation<br />
Casting Time: 	8 	Recast Time: 	2.25<br />
Fizzle Time: 	2.5 	Resist: 	Fire<br />
Resist Adjust: 	-10 	Range: 	200<br />
Location: 	Any 	Time of Day: 	Any<br />
Deletable: 	No 	Interruptable: 	Yes<br />
Target Type: 	Single 	Spell Type: 	Detrimental<br />
Category: 	Dir. Dmg [Fire] 	Source: 	Test 04/05<br />
<br />
4070 dmg base.  Assuming 25% (50% fire focus) + 15% (best flappy or bard) it is 40% more, on average, assuming ZERO resists or: 5698 average hit with a bard.<br />
<br />
23% of casts however, will land for full damage, and do double damage with destructive fury.<br />
<br />
That gives, (4070 * 2 ) * 1.5 + 4070 * .4 average crit = 13838 average crit with a bard and a fully debuffed mob.<br />
<br />
So, weighted average of .77 hits at 5698, and .23 crits at 13838 is 7570 damage.<br />
<br />
Cast time, with maxed spell haste, maxed item haste, cleric spell haste is 8 * 57% (23% item haste, 10% BoV, 10% quick damage maxed) + 2.5 second recast, 7.06 seconds per cycle.<br />
<br />
That gives, 1072 damage/second.<br />
<br />
Core-fire, consumes 850 base mana.  With 20% mana preservation, specialize evocation, that is around 23% average saving, or 655 mana per cast.  At one cast every 7.06 seconds, a wizard consumes 92.70 mana per second.  With every single raid buff, a truly top end wizard might regain around ~16 mana per second, giving a net loss of ~77 mana per second.  With a 12k mana pool, a wizard will be able to sustain this for 155 seconds.<br />
<br />
155 seconds of 1072 damage/second is 167064 damage.<br />
<br />
Let's analyze what is necessary for a wizard to achieve this:<br />
50% fire damage focus.  Currently one item in game with this focus, and drops from Vishmar, top end DoN boss.<br />
20% mana preservation.  Two items in game with this effect, one from Yar Lir, and one from Vangl.<br />
23% detrimental spell haste up to level 70.  Anguish gear only.<br />
A bard to keep HoS, fire chant, ancient chant on boss to minimize resists.<br />
A bard to sing manasong, focus song.<br />
Full raid debuffs (ro's, mage malosinia, etc) and even with full debuffs most high end mobs you will still get a fair share of resists.<br />
<br />
This scenario requires some incredibly high end gear, a huge support crew dedicated to making the wizard shine, and some really good luck.<br />
<br />
I think the problem is that Panther got changed waaaay too much during DoN beta, so when the final version came around the developers did not get a chance to test it.  When I first saw that it had no recast timer I really thought it was an oversight, and I assume other people thought the same thing.  Until you reach 'saturation' or you run out of targets to panther, the spell is really really good.  I don't want to write some Thott type graphs on the spell, but I think thiis shows two things.<br />
<br />
One, int casters in general really need some love in the damage department, and two the spell should have been tested much more in Beta.  In MMORPG, it is horrible to give a very good thing no matter how overpowered then taking it away.  Even when the level 49 necromancer pet got nerfed, and it was something overpowered beyond compare, people whined and nerfed.  I think the key now is changing the spell so it is still very useful and not incredibly annoying to keep up.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
