<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Macnair</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Teacher<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Feb 2004<br />
	Location: Halas
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Mearis</b><br /><i>The problem with haste, is that encounters are balanced with haste in mind. ... Melee damage is balanced assuming they are kept hasted, and so are encounters, and so is clarity.  They are designed assuming people have those buffs.  Panthr 'breaks' this mold, and it is something 'on top'</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>I don't really find this convincing.  Here's why.<br />
<br />
Some encounters are too hard for MyGuild_01; some are yawningly easy; and some are moderately or highly challenging.<br />
<br />
Take Derakor the Vindicator in Kael Drakkel.  I bet we got wiped by him 15 times.  We knew we could take him, we just knew it:  but we failed over and over again.  <br />
<br />
Now, of course, he can readily be taken down by a solid group; by numerous trios; probably some good duos; maybe by a superb soloer (has anyone soloed Vindi? I don't know).<br />
<br />
Vindi was too hard for us because the dps and the healing we could bring was not sufficient to win the fight.  He is now easy because the dps and the healing we can bring is quite sufficient to win the fight.<br />
<br />
If the encounter with Vindi is 'balanced,' it is balanced at the point in the life of MyGuild_01 where it is a hard-but-winnable fight.  If we do everything right we will win; if we mess up some stuff we'll lose.<br />
<br />
If we are well prior to that point, adding more dps won't help us enough to get us into the hard-but-winnable category.  We will wipe at 30% instead of at 55% -- but we'll still lose.<br />
<br />
If we are well past that point, then more dps means instead of killing Vindi in 50 seconds, we'll kill him in 40 seconds.  <br />
<br />
If we are just prior to that point, the encounter is not quite balanced:  but adding more dps could make it balanced.  So instead of "this encounter will be hard-but-winnable (="balanced") in another three weeks, when we have a little bit better gear and all" -- it's hard-but-winnable (="balanced") now, with the additional dps.<br />
<br />
Every encounter in the game is like that.  With the spells, gear, and aa available today to MyGuild_01, some encounters will be trivial, some will be balanced, and some will be impossible.  <br />
<br />
It does not make sense to say that Vindi was designed on the assumption that the raid would be hasted, so it is fine for enchanters to provide massive cooperative dps (that won't make Vindi too easy); but Vindi was not designed on the assumption that shamans could provide hefty cooperative dps as well, so it would be wrong for shamans to be able to do that (that would make Vindi too easy).  No.  Vindi (or any other mob) will be too easy, too hard, or a good challenge, depending on the overall skills, spells, gear, and aa that MyGuild_01 can bring:  including haste, including heals, including buffs like Leopard.<br />
<br />
If Spirit of Leopard had been available back in those good old days, it might have meant that Vindi would have wiped us only 6 times instead of 15, before we got it figured out.  We would have advanced a little more quickly.  But hey, it still looks like we would have advanced from the point where the encounter with Vindi was impossible, through the point where the encounter was balanced, and on to where the encounter was trivial.</p>
	
	
	
