<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Sir Yakk</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Lurker<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Mar 2002<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>The differnce between haste and panther is stackability.<br />
<br />
There are 3 classes in game who can give full haste to anyone.  BST, Shaman and Enchanters.<br />
<br />
Only one of their hastes work on a person.<br />
<br />
At 400,000 damage over a 5 minute fight in a 54 sized raid with 40 valid perminate and the occasional temoporary pet+melee targets, 3-4 shamans can stack doing nothing but casting this spell.<br />
<br />
That is the difference between haste and this spell.  The gain on the margin.  The marginal gain from adding a 2nd enchanter, haste-wise, is 0.  In a raid containing BSTs and Shamans, the marginal gain from adding 1 enchanter for haste is freeing 1 shaman from an annoying chain-cast-haste duty, or a 5% melee DPS upgrade (going from 191% haste with shaman group buff to 200% haste).  The 2nd enchanter... does nothing.<br />
<br />
If panther had a 1% slow component (nullifying haste), or if only 1 of 3 different could generate that 400,000 panther-damage, then you'd be correct in comparing haste and panther.<br />
<br />
I was calculating a theoretical maximium.  Putting forward a way of nerfing the spell in a way that reduces the theoretical maximium without lowering the practical result nearly as much may fall out of this.<br />
<br />
A 10 shot proc-count might do this.  It weakens panther where it is very strong, and does not harm panther where it is weaker (ie, you only have an NPC engaged 50% of the time panther is up).</p>
	
	
	
	
	
