	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Sir Yakk</b><br /><i>The differnce between haste and panther is stackability.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote> ... and that haste is on for an hour at a time, and that one cast of haste already adds well over twice the damage that 36 casts of panther can do.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Sir Yakk</b><br /><i>over a 5 minute fight in a 54 sized raid with 40 valid perminate and the occasional temoporary pet+melee targets, 3-4 shamans can stack doing nothing but casting this spell.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote> Ummm.  Two shamans, sure.  Three, if you like, only have to do 13 targets each.  What's the fourth one supposed to do?  You can't stack four or five or six shamans to cast this buff.  You can add more nukers or more melees to cause direct damage, and they all stack.  But buffers don't stack so well, it's true. <br />
<br />
If you can get Panther onto 40 targets successfully at the raid, that means your three shamans, casting buffs as fast as they can go, will just about match the buff-caused cooperative dps of one enchanter casting one spell per hour.<br />
<br />
Your argument seems to be this.  Three shamans working together frantically can provide Panther buffs that add perhaps 2400 burst dps to a raid fight. One enchanter can provide a haste buff to add 2400 dps to a raid fight.  A second enchanter, however, cannot provide another copy of that haste buff to add an additional 2400 dps to that raid fight.  Because that second enchanter cannot buff to provide for a second 2400 dps, three shamans should not be able to buff to provide 2400 dps even once.</p>
	
	
	
